export const notes = "<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>1. Causes of Deforestation</h3>\n  <p>Deforestation is the permanent removal of trees and forests. It occurs at approximately <strong>10 million hectares per year</strong> globally (FAO).</p>\n\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">Global deforestation rate: ~10 million hectares lost per year (net). Since 1990, ~420 million hectares of forest have been destroyed — an area larger than India.</div>\n\n  <h4>Agriculture (Primary Cause)</h4>\n  <p>Agriculture is the <strong>number one cause</strong> of deforestation worldwide, driven by consumer demand from wealthy nations for beef, palm oil, soy, and timber.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Cattle ranching</strong> accounts for approximately <strong>80% of deforestation in the Amazon</strong>. Land is cleared for pasture to supply global beef markets.</li>\n    <li><strong>Palm oil plantations</strong> in Borneo and Sumatra have expanded massively since the 1990s. Palm oil is found in ~50% of supermarket products.</li>\n    <li><strong>Soy farming</strong>: Brazil produces vast quantities of soy — much fed to livestock in Europe and Asia.</li>\n    <li><strong>Subsistence farming (slash and burn)</strong>: Small farmers clear and burn patches of forest. Ash temporarily fertilises soil, but soil becomes infertile in 2–3 years, forcing further clearing.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Commercial Logging</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Timber harvested for furniture, construction, and paper/pulp industries.</li>\n    <li><strong>Legal and illegal logging</strong> both occur — illegal logging is harder to control.</li>\n    <li><strong>Selective logging</strong> removes only certain tree species; <strong>clear-cutting</strong> removes all trees in an area.</li>\n    <li>Logging roads open up previously inaccessible forest, enabling further encroachment by farmers and settlers.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Mining</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Iron ore, gold, bauxite, and coal mining require clearing forest for operations.</li>\n    <li>Mining creates access <strong>roads into remote forest areas</strong>, enabling further settlement and deforestation.</li>\n    <li>Infrastructure built for mining (power lines, settlements) causes additional forest loss.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Urbanisation and Infrastructure</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Roads, settlements, hydroelectric dams, and airports cut through forest.</li>\n    <li>Example: <strong>Belo Monte Dam</strong> in the Amazon — flooded vast areas of rainforest and displaced indigenous communities.</li>\n    <li>Roads fragment habitats and provide access routes for illegal loggers and settlers.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">Exam tip: When asked to explain a cause, always link the human activity to why tropical rainforests are specifically targeted (e.g., fertile soil underneath, global demand for commodities).</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>2. Environmental Effects of Deforestation</h3>\n\n  <h4>Biodiversity Loss</h4>\n  <p>Tropical rainforests contain over <strong>50% of the world's species</strong> despite covering only ~6% of land area.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Habitat destruction leads to species extinction — estimated <strong>137 species lost per day</strong> in the Amazon alone.</li>\n    <li><strong>Endemic species</strong> (found nowhere else) are most vulnerable — once habitat is gone, the species is gone forever.</li>\n    <li><strong>Keystone species</strong> loss (e.g., top predators, pollinators) disrupts entire food webs and ecosystem function.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Climate Change Contribution</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Forests store approximately <strong>45% of terrestrial carbon</strong>. When trees are burned or decay, CO&#8322; is released.</li>\n    <li>Deforestation is responsible for <strong>10–15% of global greenhouse gas emissions</strong> — a major driver of climate change.</li>\n    <li>The Amazon alone, if fully deforested, would release enough CO&#8322; to significantly accelerate global warming.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">Deforestation contributes 10–15% of global greenhouse gas emissions. Forests store ~45% of all carbon found on land.</div>\n\n  <h4>Soil Erosion and Land Degradation</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Tree roots bind soil together. Without trees, <strong>heavy tropical rainfall washes away topsoil</strong> (surface runoff).</li>\n    <li>Tropical <strong>laterite soils</strong> are especially vulnerable — rich in iron/aluminium oxides, they become hard and infertile when exposed.</li>\n    <li>Soil compaction reduces water infiltration → increased runoff → gully erosion → eventual <strong>desertification</strong>.</li>\n    <li>Loss of humus (decaying organic matter) means soil loses fertility rapidly.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Increased Flooding</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Tree canopy <strong>intercepts rainfall</strong>, slowing its impact on the ground. Roots absorb water, reducing runoff.</li>\n    <li>Without trees, surface runoff dramatically increases → rivers flood more quickly and severely.</li>\n    <li><strong>Bangladesh floods</strong> are partly linked to deforestation in the Himalayas upstream — more runoff reaches rivers faster.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Water Cycle Disruption</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Trees release water vapour through <strong>transpiration</strong>, contributing to cloud formation and local rainfall.</li>\n    <li>The Amazon generates its own rainfall — described as \"<strong>flying rivers</strong>\": moisture transpired by trees moves westward, generating rain over the continent.</li>\n    <li>Deforestation reduces transpiration → less rainfall in the region → local climate becomes drier and hotter.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">Exam tip: For full marks on effects questions, explain the CHAIN of consequences: deforestation → soil exposed → rain hits bare soil → topsoil washed away → rivers silt up → flooding worsens downstream.</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>3. Social and Economic Effects of Deforestation</h3>\n\n  <h4>Displacement of Indigenous Communities</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Approximately <strong>3,344 indigenous territories globally</strong> are affected by deforestation.</li>\n    <li>Indigenous peoples lose their land, homes, cultural practices, and traditional knowledge.</li>\n    <li>Medicinal plant knowledge — much not yet recorded by science — is permanently lost when forest communities are displaced.</li>\n    <li>Displacement sometimes involves <strong>violent conflict</strong> between indigenous groups and loggers or government forces.</li>\n    <li><strong>Human rights abuses</strong> are documented in many deforestation frontiers (Brazil, DRC, Indonesia).</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Loss of Forest-Dependent Livelihoods</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Millions of people depend on forests for food, clean water, medicines, and building materials.</li>\n    <li>Forest loss destroys these resources, pushing communities into poverty.</li>\n    <li><strong>Ecosystem services</strong> lost include: clean water filtration, pollination of crops, natural pest control, climate regulation.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Short-Term Economic Gains</h4>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Logging generates immediate cash profit.</li>\n        <li>New farmland creates jobs and food production.</li>\n        <li>Mining revenues fund government services.</li>\n        <li>Infrastructure opens up regions to development.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Long-Term Economic Losses</h4>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Ecosystem services lost: valued at <strong>$2–5 trillion/year</strong> globally.</li>\n        <li>Soil degradation reduces agricultural productivity long-term.</li>\n        <li>Reduced rainfall harms farming and water supply.</li>\n        <li>Eco-tourism potential permanently destroyed.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <h4>Food Security</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>In the long term, soil degradation following deforestation reduces the land's ability to support agriculture.</li>\n    <li>Smallholder farmers practising slash-and-burn must keep clearing new forest as soil fertility drops.</li>\n    <li>This creates a cycle of ever-expanding forest destruction.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">Global economic cost of deforestation: estimated $2–5 trillion per year in lost ecosystem services (clean water, pollination, climate regulation, etc.).</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>4. Case Study — The Amazon Rainforest</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Location:</strong> South America, primarily Brazil<br>\n    <strong>Size:</strong> ~3 million km&#178; of tropical rainforest — the world's largest<br>\n    <strong>Status:</strong> ~17% has been lost since 1970 (as of recent estimates)\n  </div>\n\n  <h4>Key Facts</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Peak deforestation</strong>: 2003–2004 saw the highest annual rates. Improved enforcement (DETER satellite monitoring system) reduced rates in the 2010s, but deforestation rose again after 2019.</li>\n    <li><strong>Rate at peak</strong>: Equivalent to approximately <strong>26 football fields of forest lost per hour</strong>.</li>\n    <li>The Amazon River contains <strong>20% of all freshwater</strong> discharged into the world's oceans.</li>\n    <li>Over <strong>400 distinct indigenous groups</strong> live in the Amazon.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Causes in the Amazon</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Cattle ranching: 80% of deforestation</strong> — Brazil is the world's largest beef exporter.</li>\n    <li>Soy farming (much of it grown as animal feed for global livestock industries).</li>\n    <li>Logging and illegal timber trade.</li>\n    <li>Mining (gold, iron ore).</li>\n    <li>Infrastructure (roads, the Trans-Amazonian Highway, dams).</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Brazil Nut Tree — Ecosystem Interdependence Example</h4>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    The Brazil nut tree <em>cannot reproduce without intact forest</em>. It requires:\n    <ul>\n      <li>The <strong>orchid bee</strong> (its pollinator) — which depends on specific orchid species only found in intact forest.</li>\n      <li>The <strong>agouti</strong> (a large rodent, its only seed disperser) — which buries Brazil nuts and allows germination.</li>\n    </ul>\n    When forest is cleared: orchid bees disappear → no pollination → no seeds → no new Brazil nut trees → local extinction.\n    This illustrates how deforestation causes cascading ecosystem collapse.\n  </div>\n\n  <h4>The Amazon Tipping Point</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Scientists warn that if <strong>20–25% of the Amazon is deforested</strong>, it could trigger an irreversible \"dieback.\"</li>\n    <li>Reduced transpiration from fewer trees would cause the region's rainfall to decline sharply.</li>\n    <li>This could transform vast areas of Amazon rainforest into <strong>savannah (cerrado)</strong> — a process called <strong>savannification</strong>.</li>\n    <li>This is considered a <strong>climate tipping point</strong> — once passed, it cannot be reversed.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">Exam tip: The Amazon tipping point is a highly examinable concept. Learn: the threshold (20–25%), the process (reduced transpiration → less rainfall → dieback), and the consequence (irreversible savannification).</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>5. Case Study — Borneo and Sumatra</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Location:</strong> Southeast Asia (Malaysia, Indonesia, Brunei)<br>\n    <strong>Forest age:</strong> ~140 million years old — among the oldest in the world<br>\n    <strong>Status:</strong> Over 50% of Borneo's lowland forest lost since 1980\n  </div>\n\n  <h4>Palm Oil — The Primary Driver</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>39% of Borneo's deforestation</strong> is attributable to palm oil plantation expansion.</li>\n    <li><strong>Malaysia and Indonesia produce ~85% of the world's palm oil</strong>.</li>\n    <li>Palm oil is found in approximately <strong>50% of supermarket products</strong> — chocolate, shampoo, biscuits, cosmetics, margarine, soap.</li>\n    <li>Demand is driven by consumer countries in Europe, China, and India.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Endangered Species</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Bornean Orangutan</strong>: ~50,000 remain in the wild (critically endangered). Approximately <strong>3,000 are killed per year</strong> due to habitat loss and human conflict.\n      <ul>\n        <li>Require <strong>6–8 km&#178; of intact forest per individual</strong>.</li>\n        <li>Are <strong>arboreal</strong> (tree-living) — cannot cross cleared land → habitat fragmentation isolates populations and prevents genetic mixing.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Pygmy Elephant</strong> (Sabah, Borneo): Critically endangered; forest loss reduces habitat range.</li>\n    <li><strong>Sumatran Tiger</strong>: Fewer than <strong>400 remaining in the wild</strong>, entirely due to habitat loss and poaching.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Peat Forest Destruction</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Borneo and Sumatra contain vast <strong>peat swamp forests</strong> — thick layers of partially decomposed organic matter that store enormous amounts of carbon.</li>\n    <li>To plant oil palms, companies <strong>drain and burn peat forests</strong>.</li>\n    <li><strong>Indonesian peat fires (2015)</strong>: Released more CO&#8322; in a single episode than the <strong>entire US economy emits in a month</strong>. Caused a regional health crisis (smoke haze across SE Asia).</li>\n    <li>Peat fires are extremely difficult to extinguish as they burn underground.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore Connection:</strong> The 2015 Indonesian peat fires blanketed Singapore in thick haze, causing a public health emergency. PSI (Pollutant Standards Index) reached hazardous levels. This illustrates how deforestation in one country directly affects neighbouring nations.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>6. Global Deforestation Rates, Key Statistics and Exam Skills</h3>\n\n  <h4>Key Global Statistics</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>~10 million hectares</strong> of forest lost per year globally (net, after accounting for some reforestation) — FAO.</li>\n    <li>Since 1990: approximately <strong>420 million hectares</strong> of forest lost — an area larger than India.</li>\n    <li><strong>Primary forests</strong> (virgin/old-growth forest) are declining fastest — most biodiverse but often least protected.</li>\n    <li>Forests currently cover approximately <strong>31% of Earth's land area</strong>, down from ~50% in the pre-agricultural era.</li>\n    <li>Deforestation contributes <strong>10–15% of global greenhouse gas emissions</strong>.</li>\n    <li>If current rates continue, tropical rainforests could be functionally extinct within <strong>100 years</strong> (FAO warning).</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h4>Countries with Highest Deforestation Rates</h4>\n  <div class=\"example\">Brazil, Indonesia, Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Myanmar, Bolivia, Colombia — these six countries account for a disproportionate share of global forest loss.</div>\n\n  <h4>Solutions (for Evaluation Questions)</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>REDD+</strong>: UN programme paying developing countries to protect forests (reduces emissions from deforestation).</li>\n    <li><strong>Sustainable certification</strong>: RSPO (Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil) certifies sustainably produced palm oil.</li>\n    <li><strong>Consumer boycotts</strong>: Reducing demand for products linked to deforestation.</li>\n    <li><strong>Debt-for-nature swaps</strong>: Rich nations cancel developing nation debt in exchange for forest protection.</li>\n    <li><strong>National parks and reserves</strong>: Legally protecting forest areas from development.</li>\n    <li><strong>Satellite monitoring</strong>: Brazil's DETER system detects deforestation in near-real-time.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    Key numbers to memorise:<br>\n    10 million ha/year lost | 420 million ha lost since 1990 | 31% of land is forest | 10–15% of GHG emissions | Amazon: 3 million km&#178;, 17% lost, 80% cattle | Borneo: 50% lowland forest gone, 39% from palm oil | Orangutan: 50,000 left | Sumatran tiger: &lt;400\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    Exam tip — \"Suggest\" and \"Evaluate\" questions:<br>\n    Always explain WHY your suggestion would work (mechanism).<br>\n    Use \"However...\" to show evaluation — consider limitations and drawbacks.<br>\n    Example: \"Introducing satellite monitoring would reduce illegal logging because authorities can detect deforestation in near-real-time and respond quickly. However, enforcement in remote areas remains difficult, and corrupt officials may ignore alerts.\"\n  </div>\n</div>";
